0.body: This is the user guide for Prusti - a Rust verifier built upon the the Viper verification infrastructure . This guide replaces the wiki-based tutorial from the GitHub repository.
0.title: Introduction

10.body: There are two ways to enable overflow checks in Prusti, depending on how you use the tool: If you use Prusti from the IDE, create a file named Prusti.toml containing CHECK_OVERFLOWS=true in the same folder of the program that you want to verify. If you run Prusti from the command line, place the Prusti.toml in the folder from which you run Prusti, or set the PRUSTI_CHECK_OVERFLOWS=true environment variable. By default, overflow checks are disabled and Prusti models each integer type as an unbounded integer. When overflow checks are enabled, instead, Prusti models integers as bounded values with a range that depends on the type of the integer. Values of u32 types, for example, would be modeled to be between 0 and 2^32 - 1.

10.title: Overflow checks

11.body:
In Prusti, the externally observable behaviour of a function can be specified with preconditions and postconditions. They can be provided using Rust attributes : extern crate prusti_contracts;
use prusti_contracts::*; #[requires(...)]
#[ensures(...)]
fn example() { ... } #[requires(...)] is a precondition, #[ensures(...)] is a postcondition. There can be any number (including none) of preconditions and postconditions attached to a function. When no precondition is specified, #[requires(true)] is assumed, and likewise for postconditions. The expression inside the parentheses of requires or ensures should be a Prusti specification . Preconditions are checked whenever the given function is called. Postconditions are checked at any exit point of the function, i.e. explicit return statements, as well as the end of the function body.

2.body: The easiest way to try out Prusti is by using the "Prusti Assistant" extension for Visual Studio Code . Please confer the extension's webpage for detailed installation instructions. To update the currently installed version of Prusti within Prusti Assistant, it suffices to open the Command Palette and run the command Prusti: update dependencies. Warning: Some of the Prusti-specific syntax described in this guide is currently only available in the "nightly" build channel, which corresponds to the latest development version of Prusti. The settings for switching to this version in Prusti Assistant are found in File → Preferences → Settings → Prusti Assistant → Build Channel.

22.body: Prusti specifications are a superset of Rust boolean expressions. They must be deterministic and side-effect free. Therefore, they can only call only pure functions . The extensions to Rust expressions are summarised below: Syntax Meaning old(...) Value of expression in a previous state ... ==> ... Implication forall(...) Universal quantifier ... |= ... Specification entailment
22.title: Specification syntax

23.title: Old expressions

24.body:
Implications express a relationship between two boolean expressions: #[pure]
#[ensures(result ==> self.len() == 0)]
#[ensures(!result ==> self.len() > 0)]
pub fn is_empty(&self) -> bool; There is no syntax for logical equivalences ("if and only if"), because this coincides with ==: #[pure]
#[ensures(result == (self.len() == 0))]
pub fn is_empty(&self) -> bool;
24.title: Implications

25.body:
Quantifiers are typically used for describing how a method call changes a container such as a vector: #[requires(0 <= index && index < self.len())]
#[ensures(self.len() == old(self.len()))]
#[ensures(self.lookup(index) == value)]
#[ensures( forall(|i: usize| (0 <= i && i < self.len() && i != index) ==> (self.lookup(i) == old(self.lookup(i))) )
)]
pub fn store(&mut self, index: usize, value: i32) { ...
} There may be multiple bound variables: forall(|x: isize, y: isize| ...) The syntax of quantifiers is: forall(|<bound variable>: <bound variable type>, ...| <filter> ==> <expression>)
25.title: Quantifiers

26.body: Specification entailments provide the contract for a given closure or function variable. See the specification entailments chapter for more details.

3.body: Alternatively, Prusti can be set up by downloading the precompiled binaries available from the project page. We currently provide binaries for Windows, macOS, and Ubuntu. Releases marked as "Pre-release" may contain unstable or experimental features. For a command-line setup with Prusti built from source, please confer the developer guide .
3.title: Command-line setup

5.body: When the Prusti Assistant extension is active, Rust files can be verified in one of the following ways: By clicking the "Verify with Prusti" button in the status bar. By opening the Command Palette and running the command "Prusti: save and verify this file". By saving a Rust document, if "Verify on save" is enabled. By opening a Rust document, if "Verify on open" is enabled. See the following chapter for a list of verification features available in Prusti.
5.title: Prusti Assistant

6.body: To run Prusti on a file using the command-line setup: $ prusti-rustc --edition=2018 path/to/file.rs
6.title: Command line

7.title: Introductory example

8.body: Even if no specifications are provided, Prusti is capable of verifying a few basic properties about the supplied Rust code. These properties include: Absence of panics Overflow checks More intricate properties require users to write suitable specifications . The following features are either currently supported or planned to be supported in Prusti: Pre- and postconditions Trusted functions Pure functions Predicates External specifications Loop body invariants Pledges Trait contract refinement Closures Specification entailments By default, Prusti only checks absence of panics. Moreover, Prusti verifies partial correctness. That is, it only verifies that terminating program executions meet the supplied specification.
8.title: Verification Features
